<!DOCTYPE html>
<html >
<head>
  <title>Block vs Inline Elements</title>
  <style>
    .block-example, .inline-example {
      margin-bottom: 20px;
    }
    .block-box, .inline-box {
      border: 2px solid black;
      padding: 10px;
      margin: 5px;
    }
    .block-box {
      display: block;
      background-color: #d0f0fd;
    }
    .inline-box {
      display: inline;
      background-color: #fdd0d0;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>

  <h1>Block vs Inline Elements in HTML</h1>

  <p>
    In HTML, elements are classified into two main types based on how they behave in the document layout: <strong>Block</strong> and <strong>Inline</strong>.
  </p>

  <div class="block-example">
    <h2>Block Elements</h2>
    <p>Block elements:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Start on a new line</li>
      <li>Take up the full width available</li>
      <li>Can contain other block or inline elements</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Examples:</p>
    <div class="block-box">This is a &lt;div&gt; (Block)</div>
    <p class="block-box">This is a &lt;p&gt; (Block)</p>
    <h3 class="block-box">This is a &lt;h3&gt; (Block)</h3>
  </div>

  <div class="inline-example">
    <h2>Inline Elements</h2>
    <p>Inline elements:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Do not start on a new line</li>
      <li>Only take up as much width as needed</li>
      <li>Can only contain text or other inline elements</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Examples inside a sentence:</p>
    <p>
      <span class="inline-box">&lt;span&gt;</span> and 
      <a href="#" class="inline-box">&lt;a&gt;</a> and 
      <strong class="inline-box">&lt;strong&gt;</strong> are inline elements.
    </p>
  </div>

</body>
</html>
